metadata.name: CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE #168
metadata.description:
1 of 5 in CENTURY-XXX, Series 2
Edition of 1000

Tribute to Herbert W. Franke
“In Honor of the Dinosaur of Computer Art” 

Herbert W. Franke, a pioneer of computer art, passed away on July 16, 2022 at the age of 95. CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE is an homage to Franke’s MONDRIAN software developed for the Texas Instruments TI 99/4 home computer in 1979, and it’s a fundraiser to digitize his archive:

“Our goal is to raise 20,000 Euro so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. If we raise more money, it will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.” 

Each frame, a single “pixel” is added to the CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE image. When the software first loads, 100,000 frames are run in the background to start things off. Keep it running for hours or days to see it transform entirely — it’s an “infinite animation.”

metadata.name: Toupie-Néon #88
metadata.description:
Multicolor particles sampling space in 2D to give birth to 3D shapes in rotation.
Put any rythmic music you like and watch it in a dark room till your retina is printed with psychedelic patterns.

My most complex generator in the ideas yet the simplest in implementation & most unpredictable in the results with high diversity and peculiar rarities.
It's cheap because I'd like to see many variations of this generator so mint a lot ;)

You can navigate the scene, snapshot it, fly over it or just watch it.

WARNING: Webgl/GPU strongly advised for smoothness, CPU/mobile compliant with certainly heavy lag. 2K/4K/8K resolutions will burn your GPU ;)

Controls:
- H: hide/show help.
- Click/Move mouse - orbit control
- Dblclick/Space - start/pause animation.
- I: hide/show info panel. Click for panels (info, FPS).
- A-Q/D - resolution down/up (720p, 1080p, 2K, 4K, 8K)
- S - export full resolution pix (up to 8K)
- W-Z/C - rotation speede down/up
- F - fly mode on/off
- X/V - fly speed down/up

Toupie-Néon @naibdian 2022 using Opensource WebGL, ThreeJS libs, Inigo Quilez FBM noise functions.

metadata.name: Abstract Comic #20
metadata.description:
Comics were the trigger for my first absolute rapture. It was so intense that I couldn't wait to get home from school to dive into my secret box of comics and, for a few hours, escape to the world of superheroes. And, at least for a short time, be taken away from reality in which I was ostracized from society at school only because I liked math, and because I thought Spiderman and Batman were cool.

Decades later, the only thing that can be compared to the appearance of comics is the discovery of generative art. I haven't felt such a boyish trance since the appearance of the comics. And nothing has come more naturally than trying to unite my two loves.

This piece tries to achieve a comic vibe using abstract shapes and tries to convey the texture of the paper, which was of poor quality but had the most beautiful smell in the world. It was a challenge to create dynamics, action, movement, fight, and childlike joy all at the same time. Each color palette is inspired by some of the most famous comic book heroes and villains. But by far the biggest challenge was making this piece a direct link to childhood for all of you.

I sincerely hope that I succeeded.


Options:

- press 's' to save the PNG image of the current view
- press 'd' to save a hi-res PNG image

Created using p5.js
Bajiru, January 2023.

metadata.name: Richter #55
metadata.description:
Richter is the second collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog, following their first project called Gerhard. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time.
 
Richter works with data from 4 of 24 highres images, 30mb in total. This is the maximum size fxhash allows for a project and three times more than Gerhard. Richard Nadler created stunning new textures, enabling more variation in composition and detail to emerge at much higher resolution. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Richter elevates the approach from Gerhard with new methods for the realtime rendering process and new features like offline-first caching. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels as data.
 
Richter is featured in the exhibition "Generative Abstraction" at Expanded.art in Berlin.
 
- Click to start a new layer of motion and color.
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen.
- Press “s” to save the canvas.
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

leanderherzog.ch/2023/richter/
leanderherzog.ch/2022/gerhard/

metadata.name: Hashed Cities #270
metadata.description:
This token generates a deterministic set of minimal, abstract buildings of varying widths, heights, transparencies, and patterns, assembling a skyline view of your own unique imaginary city. Each city comes with its own randomized city day.

Each mint has a native setting (Day or Night) which combined with the current time of viewing influences real-time movements of celestial bodies in your mint, e.g. on a mint with the Day setting, the sun will only appear when viewed during the day. The piece will re-render every minute.

The individual strokes of this token feature some of my latest developments of an algorithm that generatively simulates the texture of print imperfections. They are randomized at each render to give it a unique character. Note that depending on the complexity of each mint, some renders may introduce a brief pause. The aesthetics are greatly inspired by plotter art of early computer artists such as 'City Painting' by Grace C. Hertlein.

Made in p5js
Created Nov 2021
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: Acequia #170
metadata.description:
Acequia (“ah-seh-kee-uh”) - a Spanish adaptation of the Arabic word as-sāqiya, meaning “water carrier”. 

In our second collaboration, Rich and Rick are back with our blend of generative code, intricate design, attention to detail, and a splash of charm. 

 Acequias are traditional irrigation canals used to distribute rainwater and snowmelt along a complex network of narrow channels. They are found in Spain, the American Southwest, and northern Mexico, where they are essential for sustaining fields, orchards, and gardens in semi-arid regions.   
Our aim in this series is to capture the essence of these waterways in bold geometric designs. Each piece is inspired by a mountain village or town in Andalusia (southern Spain). 

The location determines the cube designs and construction rules that are used to build the final output. These are combined with striking day/night palettes, outline styles, scales, climates, and a few surprises of course!


Controls (in live view): 

- Press [p] to pause water animation 
- Press [e] to complete water animation 
- Press [r] to reset water animation 
- Press [s] to save the current image 
- Press [h] for a high-res output suitable for printing 
- Press [b] to toggle the border
